properties.Title: Blowing Snow Advisory In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Poor visibility in snow and blowing snow is expected or occurring in some locations. A spring storm, tracking through southwestern Saskatchewan, is bringing an assortment of weather to southern Saskatchewan over the weekend. In general, the worst conditions are forecast to occur south of a line stretching from Kindersley to Oxbow. In this area significant wet snowfall is expected with the highest accumulations occurring over the Cypress Hills and Assiniboia areas. Blizzard and Winter Storm warnings are currently in effect for these regions. North of this line, including Regina and the Trans-Canada Highway east to the Manitoba border, snowfall amounts will be significantly less. Amounts near the Trans-Canada Highway may reach 5 cm but fall dramatically as one heads north. The wet nature of the snow will make snowfall amounts highly variable. Despite the lower snowfall amounts, northerly winds in the area will combine with the falling snow creating poor visibilities in blowing snow this morning with visibilities improving by midday. ### Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility in some locations. Blowing snow advisories are issued when winds are expected to create blowing snow giving poor visibility to 800 metres or less for at least 3 hours. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to SKstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #SKStorm.
Expires: 2019-04-28T19:59:46-00:00

properties.Title: Blizzard Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Blizzard conditions with poor visibility in snow and blowing snow are expected or occurring. A low pressure system, currently over Quebec, will track northward and impact Coral Harbour and Naujaat today. This system is forecast to bring snow and strong northerly winds gusting up to 80 km/h to these communities resulting in poor visibilities in blowing snow. Blizzard conditions are expected to develop in Coral Harbour this morning then spread to the Naujaat region this afternoon with conditions gradually improving overnight or Monday morning. ### Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NUstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NUStorm.

properties.Title: Winter Storm Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Hazardous winter conditions are expected. A Spring storm continues to give strong winds, heavy snow, and blowing snow to southern Alberta. Strong northerly winds with gusts near 90 km/h combined with heavy falling snow continue to create reduced visibilities in blowing snow. Localized whiteout conditions are expected. Total snowfall amounts of 10 to 20 cm are expected with locally higher amounts near 30 cm possible. Heavy snow and strong winds will taper off from the north this morning. ### Rapidly accumulating snow could make travel difficult over some locations. Visibility will be suddenly reduced to near zero at times in heavy snow and blowing snow. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ABstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ABStorm.

properties.Title: Winter Storm Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Hazardous winter conditions are expected. A low pressure system moving through southwestern Saskatchewan is bring snow and strong northerly winds to regions in southern Saskatchewan today. Strong northerly winds gusting to 70 km/h in combination with falling snow will also cause visibilities to be significantly reduced in blowing snow. Conditions are expected to improve over the Kindersley and Outlook areas Sunday morning with areas to the southeast improving in the afternoon ### Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Winter storm warnings are issued when multiple types of severe winter weather are expected to occur together. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to SKstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #SKStorm.

properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snowfall with total amounts of 10 to 20 cm is expected. A Spring storm over Alberta brought heavy snow to west-central regions of the province and continues to give heavy snow to southern regions. As the storm continues to track south this evening, heavy snow will spread into more southern regions of Alberta. Snowfall totals are expected to be in the 10 to 20 cm range with locally higher amounts up to 30 cm over higher terrain. The heavy snow will continue to taper off from the north this evening and overnight, except in the southern foothills where snow should linger into Sunday morning. ### Rapidly accumulating snow could make travel difficult over some locations. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ABstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ABStorm.

properties.Title: Winter Storm Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Hazardous winter conditions are expected. A Spring storm continues to give heavy snow and blowing snow to southern Alberta. In the wake of the cold front passing through the province tonight, expect very strong northerly winds gusting as high as 100 km/h. These strong winds combined with heavy falling snow will lead to reduced visibilities in blowing snow. Localized whiteout conditions are expected. Total snowfall amounts of 10 to 20 cm are expected with locally higher amounts near 30 cm possible. Heavy snow and strong winds will taper off from the north overnight and into Sunday morning. ### Rapidly accumulating snow could make travel difficult over some locations. Visibility will be suddenly reduced to near zero at times in heavy snow and blowing snow. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ABstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ABStorm.

properties.Title: Rainfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Rain, heavy at times is expected. A total of 25 to 50 millimetres of rain is expected. Combined with the melting of the snow on the ground, the rain is forecast to accelerate the spring freshet process. ### Heavy downpours can cause flash floods and water pooling on roads. Rainfall warnings are issued when significant rainfall is expected. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to QCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #QCStorm.
